            <section class="mt-10 prose">
              <h2>How this candle making calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for both beginners and experienced
                chandlers. It combines the best practices from popular tutorials
                and professional guides into a single, easy workflow:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Estimate the usable volume of your container (diameter and
                  fill height).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Convert that volume to wax weight using realistic wax
                  densities.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply your chosen fragrance load (%) to calculate fragrance
                  oil weight.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Suggest a wick size range based on wax type and container
                  diameter.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>1. Container volume</strong> (assuming a cylindrical
                  container):
                </p>
                <p>\( V = \pi \times r^2 \times h \)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( r \) = radius (half of the diameter)</li>
                  <li>\( h \) = fill height</li>
                  <li>
                    Units are converted so that volume ends up in milliliters
                    (ml ≈ cm³).
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>2. Wax weight from volume</strong>:</p>
                <p>\( \text{Wax weight} = V \times \rho_{\text{wax}} \)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( \rho_{\text{wax}} \) = wax density (g/ml)</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>3. Fragrance oil weight</strong>:</p>
                <p>
                  Let \( p \) be the fragrance load in % of total candle
                  weight.<br />
                  \( \text{Fragrance} = \dfrac{p}{100 - p} \times \text{Wax
                  weight} \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>4. Total candle weight</strong>:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Total weight} = \text{Wax weight} + \text{Fragrance}
                  \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Typical fragrance load limits by wax type</h3>
              <p>
                Always check your wax manufacturer’s technical sheet, but these
                ranges are common:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Soy container wax:</strong> 6–10% (some specialty
                  waxes up to 12%)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Paraffin container wax:</strong> 8–12%</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Beeswax:</strong> 4–8% (often used with lower loads or
                  unscented)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Blends:</strong> follow the manufacturer’s
                  recommendation, often 6–10%
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator warns you if your chosen fragrance load is
                unusually high for the selected wax type.
              </p>

              <h3>How wick suggestions are estimated</h3>
              <p>
                Wick selection is part science, part testing. This calculator
                uses your container diameter and wax type to suggest a
                <em>range</em> of wick sizes that typically work:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Small jars (&lt; 5&nbsp;cm / 2&quot;): small wicks or single
                  cotton wicks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Medium jars (5–7.5&nbsp;cm / 2–3&quot;): medium cotton or
                  small wooden wicks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Large jars (&gt; 7.5&nbsp;cm / 3&quot;): large cotton wicks,
                  or double-wicking.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Because every wax, fragrance, dye, and container combo behaves
                differently, you should always perform a full burn test and
                adjust up or down one wick size.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for better candles</h2>
              <h3>1. Weigh, don’t measure by volume</h3>
              <p>
                Many beginner tutorials use cups or fluid ounces. For consistent
                results, always weigh wax and fragrance on a digital scale. This
                calculator outputs everything in grams or ounces for that
                reason.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Add fragrance at the right temperature</h3>
              <p>
                Each wax has an optimal temperature range for adding fragrance
                oil (often 65–75&nbsp;°C / 150–170&nbsp;°F for soy). Adding too
                hot can burn off scent; too cold can cause poor binding and
                sweating. Follow your wax datasheet.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Avoid overloading fragrance</h3>
              <p>More fragrance is not always better. Overloading can cause:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Oil pooling or sweating on top of the candle</li>
                <li>Poor burn and tunneling</li>
                <li>Increased fire risk</li>
              </ul>
              <p>If you want a stronger hot throw, try:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Using a wax designed for higher fragrance loads</li>
                <li>Choosing stronger fragrance oils</li>
                <li>Letting candles cure for 1–2 weeks before burning</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Curing time</h3>
              <p>
                Most soy and soy-blend candles benefit from 7–14 days of curing.
                Paraffin often needs less (2–5 days). Store finished candles in
                a cool, dark place with lids on during cure.
              </p>

              <h2>Example: 4 soy candles in 8&nbsp;oz jars</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you want to make four soy container candles in jars that
                are 7.5&nbsp;cm (3&quot;) in diameter and filled to 6&nbsp;cm
                height, with 8% fragrance load.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Set wax type to <strong>Soy container wax</strong>, units to
                  <strong>grams</strong>, and number of candles to
                  <strong>4</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter diameter <strong>7.5&nbsp;cm</strong> and fill height
                  <strong>6&nbsp;cm</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Set fragrance load to <strong>8%</strong> and click
                  <strong>Calculate recipe</strong>.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>The calculator will show approximately:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Total wax: around 480–500&nbsp;g</li>
                <li>Total fragrance: around 40–45&nbsp;g</li>
                <li>
                  Per candle: about 120–125&nbsp;g wax + 10–11&nbsp;g fragrance
                </li>
                <li>
                  Suggested wick: medium cotton wick suitable for a 7–8&nbsp;cm
                  soy container
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Can I use this for pillar candles or wax melts?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. For pillars, enter the approximate diameter and height of
                the finished candle. For wax melts, treat each cavity as a small
                container and enter its diameter and depth, then multiply by the
                number of melts.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my container is not perfectly round?</h3>
              <p>
                For square or oval containers, use the average of the two main
                dimensions as an “effective diameter”. For example, a 6&nbsp;cm
                × 8&nbsp;cm oval could be approximated as a 7&nbsp;cm diameter.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this calculator enough to sell candles safely?</h3>
              <p>
                No calculator can replace proper safety testing. Use this tool
                to design consistent recipes, then:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Perform multiple burn tests for each new combination of wax,
                  fragrance, dye, and container.
                </li>
                <li>Follow all local regulations and labeling requirements.</li>
                <li>
                  Use appropriate warning labels and heat-resistant containers.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
